<br>
Ok.. now to my next affirmative.<br>
<br>
&quot;Children, it is the last hour; and just as you heard that antichrist is coming, even how many antichrists have arisen, from this we know it it is the last hour.<br>
They went out from us, BUT THEY WERE NOT REALLY OF US; FOR IF THEY HAD BEEN OF US, THEY WOULD HAVE REMAINED WITH US; but they went out, in order that it might be shown that they are not of us.<br>
But you have an anointing from the Holy One, and you all know.<br>
[snip]<br>
And this is the promise which He Himself made to us; ETERNAL LIFE.&quot;<br>
~1 John 2: 18 ff<br>
<br>
Those that &quot;leave&quot; were never part of the family of God. Jesus makes this clear again in John 10.<br>
<br>
&quot;But he who enters by the door is a shepherd of the sheep.<br>
To him the doorkeeper opens; and the sheep HEAR his voice; and he calls his own sheep BY NAME, and leads them out.<br>
When he puts forth all his own, he goes before them, and the sheep follow him BECAUSE THEY KNOW HIS VOICE.<br>
And a stranger they simply will not follow, but will flee from him because they do not know the voice of the stranger.&quot;<br>
~vs 2-5.<br>
<br>
If you go on in the chapter He points out that HE is the door and He is the good shepherd.<br>
<br>
Those that are HIS, are always HIS. He goes on in verse 27:<br>
<br>
&quot;My sheep hear My voice and I know them and they follow Me;<br>
and I give ETERNAL LIFE to them; and they shall NEVER PERISH, and NO ONE shall snatch them out of My hand.<br>
My Father who has given them to Me is greater than all; and NO ONE is able to snatch them out of the Father's hand&quot;<br>
<br>
That means the believers themselves. NO ONE is stronger than Jesus and the Father. <br>
<br>
Ephesians talks about this too.<br>
<br>
&quot;In Him, you also, after listening to the message of truth, the gospel of your salvation--having also believed you WERE SEALED IN HIM with the Holy Spirit of promise&quot;<br>
~1: 13<br>
<br>
We are creatures that cannot NOT sin.. but we do become &quot;new&quot; with our faith in Jesus. As such a creature we can certainly &quot;greive&quot; the Holy Spirit, but we do not lose that &quot;seal&quot;. (I don't want to quote the whole book of Ephesians, but it's all through the first 4 chapters). We are indwelled by Him, and He promises to NOT leave us.. ever. <br>
<br>
Going back to 1 John 4: 4<br>
<br>
&quot;You are from God, little children, and have overcome them; because GREATER IS HE WHO IS IN YOU than he who is in the world&quot;<br>
<br>
And chapter 5: 4 ff<br>
<br>
&quot;For whatever is born of God overcomes the world; and this is the victory that has overcome the world--our faith.<br>
And who is the one who overcomes the world but he who believes that Jesus is the Son of God?<br>
[snip]<br>
The one who believes in the Son of God has the witness in himself;<br>
[snip]<br>
And the witness is this, that God has given us ETERNAL LIFE, and this life is in His son.<br>
[snip]<br>
These things I have written to you who believe in the name of the Son of God in order THAT YOU MAY KNOW THAT YOU HAVE ETERNAL LIFE&quot;<br>
<br>
How can it be any clearer? It is God that gives us our faith, and our faith in Jesus guarantees ETERNAL LIFE because we are sealed by the Spirit of God. He knows us by name and we follow him. As humans we can grieve Him, but he promises to never leave us.. and NO ONE can take us from Him, that includes ourselves. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#DEB887><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bsparrowshearth.showUserPublicProfile?gid=t0mmyt>T0mmyT</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle><img src=http://smilies.narno.com/smilies/yaplukon/dead.gif></span><br>  Posts: 505<br> <font color=#B87333>(12/3/03 4:16 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fsparrowshearthfrm21.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=7.topic&index=13>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> 2nd Affirmative Statement Rebuttal</span><hr size=1> DEFINITION:  By “state of grace” I mean the condition that a person is in – whether they possess ‘sanctifying’ (saving) grace or not.  If a person is in a “state of grace” and they die, then they are saved.  If a person finds oneself NOT in a “state of grace” at their death, they are NOT saved.<br>
<br>
Your conclusion regarding 1 John makes my point about personal moral assurance EXACTLY.   How then can one TRULY know one is ‘of us’?  One can become ‘born again’ at the age of 10, live a completely moral, faithful, faith-filled and holy life, and then one day at 80 decided to rob a bank, rape, kill, commit suicide and die unrepentant.  One’s self and an outsider would conclude up until that last day that one was ‘saved’ but then after that last day decide that one wasn’t “really of us”.  That doesn’t sound like personal moral assurance if the conclusion for 70 years could be wrong after all!  The people who leave in 1 John are not saved yet David (who you mentioned in the first round) leaves but yet you claim isn’t forsaken and thus still saved.  How can one possible know the difference?  Wouldn’t it be AFTER one “leaves” and find that one is forsaken that they weren’t saved even though they thought they were?  That isn’t personal moral assurance then.<br>
<br>
We already talked about John 10 but I believe you’re hinging your argument on “NO ONE” meaning not even ourselves (as you stated in your first counterpoint rebuttal) can choose to leave.  But in the first four chapters of Ephesians that you point to, there are conditional statements.  Verse 4 states “that we SHOULD walk holy and without blame before Him” – SHOULD, not will or would.  The stage then is already set for verses 11-14 where it starts with those who are “In Him” and “SHOULD (not would) be to the praise of His glory”.  The sealing refers to IF we have the Holy Spirit and if we choose not to have Him (Paul warns us not to quench the Holy Spirit in 1 Thes. 5:19) then we don’t.  With the Holy Spirit, the sanctified Christian is sealed and has the guarantee, but if one starts to walk unholy and full of blame, that person has driven out or quenched the Holy Spirit with the practice of sin.<br>
<br>
We find earlier in 1 John 3:10 that whoever does not practice righteousness is not of God.  Reminds me again of David.  Agreed that God didn’t forsake David, but David chose not to practice righteousness and thus was not of God until he repented again.  Then in 5:2 (right before your quote) we find that we must “keep his commandments”!  But if we can’t leave God why must we love and obey and keep commandments?  I whole-heartedly agree with your conclusion EXCEPT the last part that just does not follow from the context of the Scripture you quoted.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#F5F5DC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bsparrowshearth.showUserPublicProfile?gid=oneandonlyfemme>One and Only Femme</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle><span style=color:green;><b>Five-Star Drama Queen</b></span></span><br>  Posts: 322<br> <font color=#B87333>(12/5/03 3:46 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fsparrowshearthfrm21.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=7.topic&index=14>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://members.aol.com/femmeca/hohoho WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: 2nd Affirmative Statement Rebuttal</span><hr size=1> I think I'd like to explore this &quot;state of grace&quot; thing after we're finished.. maybe in a thread in the theology forum.. would you consider that?<br>
<br>
Ok.. onward...<br>
<br>
[They went out from us, BUT THEY WERE NOT REALLY OF US; FOR IF THEY HAD BEEN OF US, THEY WOULD HAVE REMAINED WITH US;<br>
~1 John 2: 18]<br>
<br>
The operative point being &quot;They would have remained&quot;. Once one is actually, factually part of God's family, they remain.<br>
<br>
If we go back to the OT examples, many, I'd even venture MOST , even ALL, of the Kings of Judah were men of God.. but they screwed up, especially near the end of their lives. EVERY last one! David, Solomon, Asa, Jesoshaphat.. all were called &quot;men of God&quot; and yet they didn't keep their lives singularly focused on God. And yet, they are remembered for not only the screw ups, but that their hearts were towards God. God sent prophets to smack them upside the head and get their mind back on track.. Some did, some didn't. But in the records, they were STILL referred to as &quot;men of God&quot;. It was sad that they let things slip in their old age, and some left a mess for their sons to deal with, or left sons that made it worse. But God continued to have His hand on them. He never forsaked them, even when they strayed. <br>
<br>
Tommy, I'm sorry, but I don't understand the stress on &quot;should&quot; as a negative. It's a reminder that that's what we strive for. But it doesn't say it's conditional of keeping our Eternal life. <br>
<br>
After it talks about being &quot;sealed to the Holy Spirit&quot; in Ephesians 1: 13, vs 14 goes further on the permanance of it:<br>
<br>
&quot;Who is given as a pledge of our inheritance, with a view to the redemption of God's own possession, to the praise of His glory&quot;<br>
<br>
We're PLEDGED and are God's OWN POSSESSION! How much more can we be assured that we will never be separated from Him.<br>
<br>
If we go forward to Ephesians 2: 4-9:<br>
<br>
&quot;But God, being rich in mercy, because of His great love with which He loved us,<br>
even when we were dead in our transgressions, made us alive together with Christ (by grace you have been saved),<br>
[snip]<br>
For by grace you HAVE BEEN saved through faith; and that not of yourselves, it is the gift of God<br>
not as a result of works, that no one should boast.&quot;<br>
<br>
If our salvation is something we cannot achieve, how can we &quot;unachieve&quot; it? Our works have nothing to do whatsoever with our salvation. It's presented here as completed.. &quot;have been saved&quot;. It's done, completed. Also, Titus points this out:<br>
&quot;He saved us Not on the basis of deeds which we have done in righteousness, but according to His mercy by the washing of  regeneration and renewing by the Holy Spirit&quot; Chapter 3: 4<br>
<br>
Also, the faith we have is a gift from God, it's not something tangible that we can take up and lay down. Our very being is changed, we go from dead in our sins to alive in Jesus. We are forever changed. The Holy Spirit comes and lives within us. And He helps us. He prays for us when we don't know how to (that's in Romans 8: 26.) <br>
<br>
Actually, all through Romans it shows that while we were slaves to sin, we become freed, and slaves to God. But, at the same time, &quot;nothing good dwells in me&quot; but &quot;there is therefore no condemnation for those who are in Christ Jesus&quot;. Chapter 7: 18 and 8: 1.<br>
<br>
Romans 4 and James 2 talk about works. They point out that works demonstrate our faith before men, but not God. He looks at our heart, he KNOWS our heart. Our works have no bearing on our salvation, but are an outward showing to others of our inward transformation.<br>
<br>
[But if we can’t leave God why must we love and obey and keep commandments?]<br>
<br>
Because we are filled with the Holy Spirit and WANT to? Because we keep our hearts toward God and rejoice in His love and mercy? Because we know it pleases Him? Because it brings us closer to Him? Because it makes our lives better? Because it demonstrates Him to others? <br>
<br>
I could go on and on.. but I think you get the drift. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#DEB887><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bsparrowshearth.showUserPublicProfile?gid=t0mmyt>T0mmyT</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle><img src=http://smilies.narno.com/smilies/yaplukon/dead.gif></span><br>  Posts: 537<br> <font color=#B87333>(12/15/03 3:07 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fsparrowshearthfrm21.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=7.topic&index=15>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Tommy's 2nd Affirmative Statement</span><hr size=1> In my opening statement I stated that the Bible shows us that salvation was an ongoing event.  Paul speaks of salvation as a past event several times.  We hear in Ephesians 2:5 that “it is by grace you HAVE BEEN saved” {again, all emphasis is mine throughout) and in verse 8 “For it is by grace you HAVE BEEN saved”.  But this past aspect is only one dimension of our salvation.  There is an ongoing aspect as well.  1 Peter 1:9 states “for you are RECEIVING the goal of your faith, the SALVATION of your souls”.  Paul tells us in Philippians 2:12 that we need to “work out your own salvation”.  Along with the past and ongoing aspect of salvation there is a future aspect as well.  We find in Roman 13:11 this sense in which we have not yet received salvation “For SALVATION IS NEARER TO US NOW than when we first believed” and in 1 Corinthians 3:15 “though he himself WILL BE SAVED” and in 5:5 “that his spirit may BE SAVED in the day of the Lord Jesus”.   Salvation has past, present and future aspects.<br>
<br>
Another aspect I’d like to develop from my opening statement and from my 2nd rebuttal is the possibility of self-delusion and delusion of others.  What of the example of the “born-again” person who lives an upstanding life until the last day?  Was this person never saved, even though he and others around him would have sworn to it?  Or can one commit all kinds of foul deeds like murder, adultery, and rape and since they’re already saved, not lose it or even have to worry about it?  Or those in Matthew 7:22-23 who cry out “’Lord, Lord, did we not prophesy in your name, and in your name drive out demons and perform many miracles?’  Then I will tell them plainly, ‘I never knew you.  Away from me, you evildoers!’”   Sounds like a group of people who THOUGHT they were saved.  If they thought it but weren’t, that doesn’t sound like true personal moral assurance.<br>
<br>
Finally I’d like to mention more Scripture that warns us because if we’re truly personally assured, why do we need a warning for something we can’t lose?   We find in Romans 11:22 “Consider therefore the kindness and sternness of God: sternness to those who fell, but kindness to you, provide that you CONTINUE in His kindness.  Otherwise, you also will be CUT OFF”.  And in 1 Corinthians 10:11-12 “These things happened to them as examples and were written down as WARNINGS for us, on whom the fulfillment of the ages has come.  So, if you THINK you are standing firm, be CAREFUL that you DO NOT FALL!”   2 Timothy 2:12 tells us that “IF we ENDURE, we will also reign with Him.  IF we DISOWN Him, He will also DISOWN US;” even though in v.13 “He will remain faithful”.  EVEN though GOD is faithful, we CAN disown Him and then He will disown us!  Hebrews 6:4-6 describes sharers in the Holy Spirit who then fall away and in 10:26-27 that judgment remains for those who continue to sin after receiving the truth.<br>
